ANNUAL FINANCIAL REPORT 2024 – STEIERMÄRKISCHE SPARKASSE GROUP 
122
38.  Restructurings, new negotiations and forbearance 
Forbearance concessions include contractual changes to the loan repayment conditions agreed with the customers. 
These include: reduction in the repayment rates, term extension, reduction or waiver of the interest, reduction or 
waiver of the credit amount, conversion of a revolving loan to payment by instalments and/or other. 
Restructurings in which concessions are made towards customers who due to existing or expected financial difficulties 
run the risk of no longer being able to meet their contractual payment obligations are deemed to be forbearance. The 
borrower is in financial difficulties when one of the following circumstances occurs: 
 the customer was in arrears by more than 30 days in the past three months; 
 the customer would have been 30 days or more in arrears if it were not for forbearance; 
 the customer is classified as non-performing/defaulting; 
 the customer would become non-performing without forbearance measures. 
 Customers that are served in a Workout unit; 
The following applies in addition for non-retail customers: 
 Customers with early warning signals; 
 customer has a deteriorated economic situation which leads to a downgrading of the internal rating; 
 customers with an increased probability of default. 
Forbearance concessions lead to performing forbearance status and exist when one of the following provisions is met: 
 an adjustment/refinancing of the contract would not have been granted if the customer had not been in financial 
difficulties; 
 the contractual conditions of the adjusted/refinanced contract are favourable towards the customer compared to 
the existing contractual conditions; 
 the adjusted/refinanced contract contains more favourable contractual conditions than other customers with a 
similar risk profile would have received from the same institute; 
 use of a conditional contractual condition; 
 Waiver of a contractual provision that is relevant to a default. 
The performing forbearance status can be rescinded and the account kept as an account without forbearance status 
if all of the following conditions are met: 
 a minimum of two years have passed since the classification of the receivable as performing forbearance (probation); 
 within the framework of the repayment agreement in the forbearance status, at least 50% of the original instalment 
before forbearance (corresponds to a material repayment) was regularly paid over at least half the probationary/trial 
period (in the case of retail customers). 
 credit repayments of a notable amount were made on a regular basis over at least half the probationary/trial period 
(in the case of corporate customers). 
 a fundamental repayment includes for all segments (retail and non-retail) the amount that was overdue or was 
written off before the granting of the forbearance measure; 
 all receivables of the customer are overdue at the end of the probationary/trial period by less than 30 days.
